    phaseImage: {fileID: 2800000, guid: 80a2091578d68d3458933a4efb4a1590, type: 3}
    phaseDesc: I did not know the answer myself. As the throbbing feet faded into
      the background of my thoughts, I questioned why humans do anything at all.
      What is the purpose of art? Does everything need to have a meaning? By the
      second day, I had fallen into a rhythm. Colorado's white-capped peaks loomed
      in the distance and wildflowers bloomed in the valley below. My pain, while
      present, was now a part of the grand experience. Philosophical thought that
      was difficult to comprehend at home seemed to come naturally now. Somewhere
      between stepping over pinecones and wading through creeks, it clicked. Did
      there need to be a reason to do anything? There was something beautiful about
      trekking an obscene amount of miles for no reason. Something inherently human
      about stretching your body to its physical limits.
